1
00:00:45,645 --> 00:00:47,414
MIKE: Why is it that
everything important

2
00:00:47,447 --> 00:00:49,516
that happens to you
when you're a kid

3
00:00:49,549 --> 00:00:51,184
happens during the summer?

4
00:00:51,217 --> 00:00:54,854
In the summer of 1971,
I was 10 years old

5
00:00:54,888 --> 00:00:58,591
and the only thing I looked
forward to more than
the last day of school

6
00:00:58,625 --> 00:01:02,762
was the first day of practice
of hydroplane racing season.

7
00:01:02,796 --> 00:01:05,165
You could say Madison kids
were born into racing

8
00:01:05,198 --> 00:01:08,735
the same way some folks
are born in the oil business
or farming.

9
00:01:09,903 --> 00:01:12,472
The town's port
on the Ohio River

10
00:01:12,505 --> 00:01:15,542
at one point had been
the busiest in the Midwest,

11
00:01:15,575 --> 00:01:17,877
but that had started
to change.

12
00:01:19,446 --> 00:01:22,649
And though the river
had given the town
its prosperity,

13
00:01:22,682 --> 00:01:25,285
boat racing had given it
her identity,

14
00:01:25,318 --> 00:01:29,489
having hosted the first
professional boat race
in the United States.

15
00:01:29,522 --> 00:01:31,991
The town even owned
its own boat.

16
00:01:32,025 --> 00:01:35,328
They called it
the
Miss Madison.

17
00:01:35,361 --> 00:01:40,166
In June of 1961,
my father climbed in
that very same boat,

18
00:01:40,200 --> 00:01:42,335
just two days
after I was born,

19
00:01:42,368 --> 00:01:44,404
and barely survived
a tragic accident,

20
00:01:44,437 --> 00:01:46,439
which ended his racing career

21
00:01:46,473 --> 00:01:48,842
and took the life
of his best friend.

22
00:01:51,077 --> 00:01:55,248
People used to say I should
have known my father
before the accident,

23
00:01:55,281 --> 00:01:57,217
that he was a different man.

24
00:01:57,250 --> 00:01:59,419
Well, that summer,
10 years later,

25
00:01:59,452 --> 00:02:02,922
he would give us
a glimpse of just
what kind of man he was.

