00:25:56,388 --> 00:25:57,822
KITTLE:
Being from San Diego,

482
00:25:57,856 --> 00:25:59,357
you know how important
this is to me.

483
00:25:59,391 --> 00:26:02,093
Well, with that
great new waterway
you guys are buildin',

484
00:26:02,127 --> 00:26:03,895
we're excited as hell
to have you onboard.

485
00:26:03,929 --> 00:26:05,764
The trouble is
findin' you a slot.

486
00:26:05,797 --> 00:26:07,899
George,
you know that my group
is very serious.

487
00:26:07,933 --> 00:26:11,703
If we get behind this race,
I can guarantee national TV.

488
00:26:11,736 --> 00:26:13,672
He's right, George.
Think about it.

489
00:26:13,705 --> 00:26:17,108
The APBA and the circuit
stand to gain
thousands of dollars.

490
00:26:17,142 --> 00:26:19,611
All right, Bill,
why don't you just tell me
what works for you?

491
00:26:19,644 --> 00:26:23,048
Well, first of all,
we'll want the Labor Day
weekend slot.

492
00:26:23,081 --> 00:26:24,950
Madison's race?
Uh-huh.

493
00:26:24,983 --> 00:26:28,019
Shoot, that means
we'd have to kick 'em
off the circuit,

494
00:26:28,053 --> 00:26:30,555
and they've been around
a long time, 1904.

495
00:26:30,588 --> 00:26:33,224
That has to be part
of the deal. Sorry.

496
00:26:33,258 --> 00:26:35,527
JIM: The guy
from San Diego
is Bill Kittle.

497
00:26:35,560 --> 00:26:38,363
Now, he's been
tryin' to get a race
on the circuit for years.

498
00:26:38,396 --> 00:26:41,333
And knowin' how much money
those guys are wavin' around,

499
00:26:41,366 --> 00:26:43,301
we're probably
lookin' at our last season.

500
00:26:43,335 --> 00:26:45,136
You mean
we can't race anymore?

501
00:26:45,170 --> 00:26:46,471
Just 'cause
we don't host a race

502
00:26:46,504 --> 00:26:49,140
don't mean
we can't have the boat
on the circuit, right?

503
00:26:49,174 --> 00:26:51,076
Travis, proceeds
from the regatta

504
00:26:51,109 --> 00:26:53,812
practically support
the entire boat operation.

505
00:26:53,845 --> 00:26:56,781
I imagine George Wallin
will make some sort of
announcement tonight.

506
00:26:56,815 --> 00:26:58,750
Hi, everybody.
I'm George Wallin,

507
00:26:58,783 --> 00:27:00,719
president of the American
Power Boat Association.

508
00:27:00,752 --> 00:27:02,754
If you don't know that
by now, I'm in deep trouble.

509
00:27:02,787 --> 00:27:04,289
(ALL LAUGHING)

510
00:27:04,322 --> 00:27:07,792
Unfortunately,
Tri-Cities has had some
sponsors fall through

511
00:27:07,826 --> 00:27:09,894
and so they will be
unable

512
00:27:09,928 --> 00:27:13,198
to host
the Gold Cup Championship
race, this year.

513
00:27:13,231 --> 00:27:15,734
And we've decided,
really, that the only
fair thing to do

514
00:27:15,767 --> 00:27:19,771
is to conduct a drawing
among the other five cities.

515
00:27:19,804 --> 00:27:22,340
And the city that is drawn
would have the right

516
00:27:22,374 --> 00:27:23,875
to host this year's Gold Cup,

517
00:27:23,908 --> 00:27:26,911
provided, of course,
that they can guarantee
the prize money,

518
00:27:26,945 --> 00:27:30,515
which is $50,000
to be deposited
by tomorrow at midnight.

519
00:27:30,548 --> 00:27:33,284
And so, the city
with the right to host

520
00:27:33,318 --> 00:27:37,222
the 1971 Gold Cup
Championship race is...

521
00:27:39,324 --> 00:27:40,692
Madison, Indiana.

522
00:27:40,725 --> 00:27:42,260
(PEOPLE MURMURING)

523
00:27:42,293 --> 00:27:47,365
Well, will somebody
from the Madison team
come on up?

524
00:27:51,703 --> 00:27:54,072
The whole damn town
isn't worth $50,000.

525
00:27:54,105 --> 00:27:55,874
(ALL LAUGHING)

526
00:27:58,309 --> 00:28:00,178
Now, Jim,

527
00:28:00,211 --> 00:28:03,515
we can pick
another card, you know,
while everybody's still here.

528
00:28:03,548 --> 00:28:07,152
You understand that
you're gonna have to come up
with this money by tomorrow.

529
00:28:07,185 --> 00:28:10,155
Come on, get on with it.
Pick somebody else.

530
00:28:10,188 --> 00:28:11,523
(INDISTINCT CHATTERING)

531
00:28:12,557 --> 00:28:14,692
The problem is,

532
00:28:16,194 --> 00:28:19,898
gettin' the money by tomorrow
may not work for us.

533
00:28:19,931 --> 00:28:22,434
(CHUCKLING)
I didn't think it would.

534
00:28:35,246 --> 00:28:40,852
You see, George,
we'd like to deposit
the money right now.

535
00:28:40,885 --> 00:28:45,490
Jim, look, we're in enough
of a time crunch as it is,
you know what I mean?

536
00:28:45,523 --> 00:28:49,060
If... If you're not really
serious, you're wastin'
everybody's time.

537
00:28:49,094 --> 00:28:51,196
Let me just
pick another card.

538
00:28:51,229 --> 00:28:54,132
$50,000 and zero cents.

539
00:28:55,333 --> 00:28:56,868
See you in Madison, George.

540
00:29:06,845 --> 00:29:09,547
This will be
the greatest news
to hit Madison in years.

541
00:29:09,581 --> 00:29:12,383
Jimmy, you ought to think
about runnin' for mayor.

542
00:29:13,151 --> 00:29:14,919
MAYOR: $50,000?

543
00:29:14,953 --> 00:29:18,256
$50,000.
Were you out of your mind?

544
00:29:18,289 --> 00:29:19,757
Come on,
let's get on with it.

545
00:29:19,791 --> 00:29:21,559
MAN 2: Yeah,
let's get on with it.

546
00:29:21,593 --> 00:29:23,161
(ALL CHATTERING)

547
00:29:23,194 --> 00:29:25,730
Folks, I called
this meeting.

548
00:29:25,764 --> 00:29:28,199
I wanted to see
where everybody stands
on this issue.

549
00:29:28,233 --> 00:29:30,235
Mr. Mayor, just in case
you didn't know,

550
00:29:30,268 --> 00:29:32,604
last week 400 people
lost their jobs.

551
00:29:32,637 --> 00:29:35,840
I'm one of 'em,
and I say we forget about
all this racing business.

552
00:29:35,874 --> 00:29:38,209
And I say we stand behind
Jimmy and the boys.

553
00:29:38,243 --> 00:29:39,444
ALL: Yes! Yeah.

554
00:29:39,477 --> 00:29:42,113
That's easy for you to say.
You work in Louisville.

555
00:29:42,147 --> 00:29:45,583
Now, folks,
I reckon we need to sell

556
00:29:45,617 --> 00:29:48,219
25,000 regatta tickets
to break even.

557
00:29:48,253 --> 00:29:50,889
Now, how many have
we sold so far, Audrey?

558
00:29:50,922 --> 00:29:54,125
Well, as of tonight, 134.

559
00:29:54,159 --> 00:29:55,426
(CROWD GROANING)

560
00:29:55,460 --> 00:29:57,195
This whole thing's a joke.

561
00:29:57,228 --> 00:30:00,231
Okay, folks, settle down.
Let me say something.

562
00:30:00,265 --> 00:30:01,900
No, no, that's fine.
I'm just...
Please.

563
00:30:01,933 --> 00:30:03,635
Just let me say something.
All right.

564
00:30:03,668 --> 00:30:07,505
Now, folks, before you vote,
Jim McCormick
has a few words to say.

565
00:30:09,774 --> 00:30:11,943
JIM:
I know that
this will be your decision,

566
00:30:11,976 --> 00:30:17,515
but I brought along
a letter that
the San Diego Racing Club

567
00:30:17,549 --> 00:30:21,352
sent to the
American Power Boat
Association last night.

568
00:30:23,488 --> 00:30:26,824
"This letter is to protest
the decision to allow Madison

569
00:30:26,858 --> 00:30:28,126
"to host the Gold Cup.

570
00:30:28,159 --> 00:30:29,327
(ALL EXCLAIMING)

571
00:30:29,360 --> 00:30:31,429
"We are not alone
in our belief

572
00:30:31,462 --> 00:30:34,432
"that the championship race
belongs in a major city,

573
00:30:34,465 --> 00:30:37,602
"not in some backwoods town
on a dirty river."

574
00:30:37,635 --> 00:30:39,504
Backwoods town?
Dirty what?

575
00:30:39,537 --> 00:30:42,407
"As you know, the good people
of San Diego..."

576
00:30:42,440 --> 00:30:45,910
(ALL PROTESTING)
Those no-good sunbathing
sons of bitches.

577
00:30:45,944 --> 00:30:49,280
We'll show them
what a real race
looks like.

578
00:30:49,314 --> 00:30:52,851
All in favor of
hosting the Gold Cup,
raise your hand.

579
00:30:52,884 --> 00:30:54,953
(ALL CHEERING)

580
00:30:59,123 --> 00:31:00,391
(CRYING)

581
00:31:26,150 --> 00:31:28,119
Honey? Honey.

582
00:31:28,152 --> 00:31:29,520
Honey, I know
what you're gonna say.

583
00:31:29,554 --> 00:31:31,656
Somethin' has to give.
Then let it give.

584
00:31:31,689 --> 00:31:34,726
I am not interested in
becoming Styrofoam king
of North America.

585
00:31:34,759 --> 00:31:35,860
Well, I know that.

586
00:31:35,893 --> 00:31:37,762
Those people
back there are me.

587
00:31:37,795 --> 00:31:39,530
They were there for me
after the accident,

588
00:31:39,564 --> 00:31:41,699
and I'm not turnin'
my back on them now.

589
00:31:43,134 --> 00:31:45,169
JAKE: Good goin'
tonight, Jimmy.

590
00:31:45,203 --> 00:31:46,437
Thank you, Jake.

591
00:31:47,739 --> 00:31:49,874
Wait just a second.

592
00:31:49,908 --> 00:31:52,377
I'll talk to you.
Just a second.

593
00:31:52,410 --> 00:31:54,879
We may need
a little help from
you folks down at the bank.

594
00:31:54,912 --> 00:31:57,181
What kind of help?
That check of Wallin's.

595
00:31:57,215 --> 00:32:00,318
If you could buy us
a week or two
before it clears.

596
00:32:00,351 --> 00:32:01,819
How am I gonna do that?

597
00:32:02,654 --> 00:32:03,821
(PHONE RINGING)

598
00:32:05,390 --> 00:32:07,892
Good morning.
Madison Bank and Trust.

599
00:32:07,925 --> 00:32:09,494
Yeah, this is George Wallin,

600
00:32:09,527 --> 00:32:11,696
president of the American
Power Boat Association,

601
00:32:11,729 --> 00:32:14,532
callin' to find out
when that $50,000
check's gonna clear.

602
00:32:14,565 --> 00:32:18,236
I'm sorry, Mr. Wallin,
you'll need to speak with
Gertie, our check processor.

603
00:32:18,269 --> 00:32:19,637
Well, put her on.

604
00:32:19,671 --> 00:32:22,507
We do check processing
on Tuesdays and Fridays.

605
00:32:22,540 --> 00:32:24,142
What is this, Mayberry?

606
00:32:24,175 --> 00:32:27,078
If you'd like, I can give
Gertie your message tonight.

607
00:32:27,111 --> 00:32:28,546
Tonight?
Yes, sir.

608
00:32:28,579 --> 00:32:29,914
At bingo.

609
00:32:29,947 --> 00:32:31,082
Bingo?

610
00:32:32,784 --> 00:32:33,951
Never mind.

611
00:32:40,158 --> 00:32:41,859
(INDISTINCT CHATTERING)

612
00:32:48,566 --> 00:32:50,468
(CHOIR SINGING)

613
00:32:59,777 --> 00:33:02,580
Audrey,
how many can you get me
from the Women's Club?

614
00:33:02,613 --> 00:33:04,849
Okay, if you can do that,
I would really appreciate it.

615
00:33:04,882 --> 00:33:06,317
Jim?

616
00:33:06,351 --> 00:33:08,820
I gotta go.
I'll call you back.
Come on. Let's go.

617
00:33:10,088 --> 00:33:12,323
MAN ON RADIO:
One-Bravo-Delta,
this is Central Station.

618
00:33:12,357 --> 00:33:13,391
You have a call.

619
00:33:13,424 --> 00:33:15,660
One-Bravo-Delta,
come in, please.

620
00:33:19,230 --> 00:33:20,531
Who is this?

621
00:33:20,565 --> 00:33:22,200
JIM: It's
Jim McCormick, Harry.

622
00:33:22,233 --> 00:33:24,035
(MOANING) Yeah?

623
00:33:24,068 --> 00:33:25,236
(STUTTERS)

624
00:33:25,269 --> 00:33:27,739
We're not gettin' enough
power from our engines

625
00:33:27,772 --> 00:33:30,508
and we really need
the prize money in
these next two races.

626
00:33:30,541 --> 00:33:32,076
Yeah?
Well, I got to thinkin'

627
00:33:32,110 --> 00:33:34,879
about your old
nitrous oxide
injection system.

628
00:33:34,912 --> 00:33:36,247
Stay away from it, Jim.

629
00:33:36,280 --> 00:33:38,916
Is any of that old
equipment still around?

630
00:33:38,950 --> 00:33:42,920
If I couldn't do anything
with that stuff
with all of Epperson's money,

631
00:33:42,954 --> 00:33:45,523
you guys don't have
a chance in hell.

632
00:33:45,556 --> 00:33:50,061
Jim, we are not
talking about blowing up
just boats and parts.

633
00:33:50,094 --> 00:33:53,131
We're talking about
blowing up drivers.

634
00:33:53,164 --> 00:33:55,133
I understand that, Harry.

635
00:33:56,134 --> 00:33:59,904
Listen, we put in a bid
to host the Gold Cup.

636
00:34:02,840 --> 00:34:03,875
(SIGHING)

637
00:34:05,143 --> 00:34:07,278
MIKE: Harry Volpi
had pioneered the use

638
00:34:07,311 --> 00:34:10,314
of nitrous-oxide injections
for boat engines.

639
00:34:10,348 --> 00:34:14,085
And we were confident
that this simple and
straightforward device

640
00:34:14,118 --> 00:34:16,254
would be the answer
to all our problems.

641
00:34:18,189 --> 00:34:21,559
Does anybody
recognize anything?

642
00:34:21,592 --> 00:34:23,227
TRAVIS: Where are
the directions?

643
00:34:23,261 --> 00:34:25,329
This stuff looks
like scuba gear.

644
00:34:25,363 --> 00:34:26,964
It's just
engine equipment.

645
00:34:26,998 --> 00:34:28,666
This is crazy.

646
00:34:28,699 --> 00:34:32,470
Harry Volpi's
blown up more boats
than the US Navy.

647
00:34:32,503 --> 00:34:34,739
MALE ANNOUNCER:
Another picture-perfect day

648
00:34:34,772 --> 00:34:36,641
in Seattle, hydroplane fans,

649
00:34:36,674 --> 00:34:39,777
as the
Miss Madison,
racin' here
on Lake Washington,

650
00:34:39,811 --> 00:34:42,146
hope to overcome
a tough start this season,

651
00:34:42,180 --> 00:34:43,648
and they hope
that the momentum

652
00:34:43,681 --> 00:34:46,951
of Madison
bein' the host city
for the 1971 Gold Cup

653
00:34:46,984 --> 00:34:48,286
will do it for 'em.

654
00:34:48,319 --> 00:34:49,787
MIKE: Get your
Gold Cup tickets.

655
00:34:49,821 --> 00:34:53,157
Labor Day weekend
in Madison, Indiana,
on the scenic Ohio River.

656
00:34:53,191 --> 00:34:55,460
Come on,
get your Gold Cup tickets.

657
00:34:55,493 --> 00:34:57,762
Sir? Ma'am?

658
00:34:57,795 --> 00:34:59,330
Injection system
checks out?

659
00:34:59,363 --> 00:35:01,332
Yep. Canisters are mounted.
She's ready to go.

660
00:35:01,365 --> 00:35:03,134
(ENGINE ROARING)
Skip, come here.

661
00:35:06,003 --> 00:35:08,606
I think we got a handle
on that nitrous system.

662
00:35:08,639 --> 00:35:11,409
When you get in open water,
go ahead and hit that
white button.

663
00:35:11,442 --> 00:35:12,977
You'll get a boost of power.

664
00:35:13,010 --> 00:35:17,181
Anything you guys can do
to make this tub go faster,
I'm all for it.

665
00:35:17,215 --> 00:35:20,952
Gold Cup tickets.
Get your Gold Cup tickets.

666
00:35:21,886 --> 00:35:24,789
Gold Cup tickets.
Get 'em now.

667
00:35:24,822 --> 00:35:27,191
Gold Cup tickets!
Get 'em now.
They're goin' fast.

668
00:35:27,225 --> 00:35:28,826
Get your Gold Cup tickets.

669
00:35:28,860 --> 00:35:31,996
Look here. Moonhead's
trying to get people
to come to his Hillbilly Cup.

670
00:35:32,029 --> 00:35:34,866
I don't see you sellin'
any Gold Cup tickets,
Epperson.

671
00:35:34,899 --> 00:35:37,969
I guess I will be soon,
since I heard that
we're hosting the Gold Cup

672
00:35:38,002 --> 00:35:40,771
since you guys haven't
sold enough tickets yet.
That's a lie.

673
00:35:40,805 --> 00:35:42,940
George Wallin's talking to
my dad about it right now.

674
00:35:42,974 --> 00:35:44,775
Why don't we just go
over there and ask him?

675
00:35:44,809 --> 00:35:46,077
You're so full of it.

676
00:35:46,878 --> 00:35:48,713
Wanna do somethin' about it?

677
00:35:50,147 --> 00:35:51,916
That's what I thought.

678
00:35:51,949 --> 00:35:55,887
A chicken, just like his dad.
Let's go.

679
00:35:59,690 --> 00:36:01,692
(CROWD CHEERING)

680
00:36:01,726 --> 00:36:03,728
MALE ANNOUNCER:
After a perfectly
timed start,

681
00:36:03,761 --> 00:36:07,331
Skip Naughton
steers the
Miss Madison
through the first turn

682
00:36:07,365 --> 00:36:09,400
right in the middle
of the pack.

683
00:36:09,433 --> 00:36:11,903
That's a 14:06
on that first corner, Jim.

684
00:36:24,015 --> 00:36:26,284
Look at Winston
tryin' to take the inside.

685
00:36:26,317 --> 00:36:28,085
It's all right.
She's lookin' good.

686
00:36:30,588 --> 00:36:32,023
ANNOUNCER:
Coming off
the fourth corner,

687
00:36:32,056 --> 00:36:34,191
the
Miss Madison
is really moving, fans,

688
00:36:34,225 --> 00:36:36,360
only a boat length
out of the lead.

689
00:36:37,695 --> 00:36:40,565
He could use it
on this stretch.

690
00:36:40,598 --> 00:36:43,968
Skip Naughton is
driving a great race,
a beautiful race,

691
00:36:44,001 --> 00:36:46,637
as he brings her
down the main strait.

692
00:36:46,671 --> 00:36:48,506
Come on, Skip, let's go.

693
00:36:49,840 --> 00:36:51,676
ANNOUNCER: Oh, God!

694
00:36:51,709 --> 00:36:54,979
A terrible explosion
has rocked the
Miss Madison.

695
00:36:55,012 --> 00:36:57,181
The entire right side...
Where's the Safety Rescue?

696
00:36:57,214 --> 00:36:58,783
Bill, Bill, come on.

697
00:36:58,816 --> 00:37:01,385
ANNOUNCER:
Skip Naughton
is swimming away.
He seems to be okay,

698
00:37:01,419 --> 00:37:05,056
but he's swimming away
from a burning, sinking boat.

699
00:37:06,290 --> 00:37:09,026
MAN: Get those hillbillies
off the water!

700
00:37:18,269 --> 00:37:22,240
Skip, listen, I thought
we had a handle on it.
I apologize, really.

701
00:37:22,273 --> 00:37:23,541
Mechanics who know
what they're doin'

702
00:37:23,574 --> 00:37:26,210
have a hard enough
time with this stuff,
let alone a gas pumper,

703
00:37:26,243 --> 00:37:28,179
a dockworker
and some retard.

704
00:37:28,212 --> 00:37:29,413
I quit.

705
00:37:57,608 --> 00:38:00,411
MIKE: The drive from Seattle
took almost three days,

706
00:38:00,444 --> 00:38:02,446
but it felt like three years.

707
00:38:02,480 --> 00:38:05,249
We returned on
a bleak Saturday afternoon.

708
00:38:05,283 --> 00:38:08,152
My father and I
had barely spoken
during the trip,

709
00:38:08,185 --> 00:38:12,823
already aware of
what this would mean
to the team and the town.

710
00:39:32,570 --> 00:39:35,506
I'm headin' down
to the boat garage
if you wanna come.

711
00:39:36,440 --> 00:39:37,541
No.

712
00:39:40,478 --> 00:39:43,347
Come on. Let's go for a ride.

713
00:39:50,855 --> 00:39:53,524
(BIRDS TWITTERING)

714
00:39:53,557 --> 00:39:56,026
Come on,
there's somethin'
I wanna show you.

715
00:40:13,277 --> 00:40:14,945
It's just up here.

716
00:40:16,680 --> 00:40:19,116
You brought me up here
to see a cave?

717
00:40:19,150 --> 00:40:21,018
Not just any cave, Son.

718
00:40:36,734 --> 00:40:38,202
(HATCH SQUEAKING)

719
00:40:39,870 --> 00:40:42,973
Your grandpa
brought me down here
when I was a little boy

720
00:40:43,007 --> 00:40:45,576
to show me what
stalactites look like.

721
00:40:45,609 --> 00:40:49,280
Claimed he discovered
this place when he was
in high school.

722
00:40:49,313 --> 00:40:52,383
Told me I was
the only person
he ever told about it.

723
00:40:52,416 --> 00:40:54,418
(BOTH PANTING)

724
00:40:58,689 --> 00:41:00,191
(JIM SIGHING)

725
00:41:00,224 --> 00:41:02,326
It's somethin' else, huh?

726
00:41:02,359 --> 00:41:04,395
Here, take a look at this.

727
00:41:06,230 --> 00:41:09,133
My dad would
have tanned my hide
if he'd ever seen this.

728
00:41:11,669 --> 00:41:16,006
I used to come up here
sometimes when I needed
to think about things.

729
00:41:16,040 --> 00:41:19,710
That's one
of the special things
about where we live.

730
00:41:19,743 --> 00:41:22,546
And it just
occurred to me today
that you never been here.

731
00:41:36,627 --> 00:41:38,229
(BIRDS TWITTERING)

732
00:41:48,439 --> 00:41:51,342
Hey, Lyle, I'm sorry.
I tried to call you
last week,

733
00:41:51,375 --> 00:41:53,110
but we had a problem
out in Seattle.

734
00:41:53,143 --> 00:41:54,345
I'll talk to you later.

735
00:41:54,378 --> 00:41:56,313
I'll call you right back.

736
00:41:56,347 --> 00:41:57,448
Jim.

737
00:41:57,481 --> 00:41:58,616
Yeah?

738
00:42:00,217 --> 00:42:01,886
We need to talk.

739
00:42:32,750 --> 00:42:33,951
Patty said
they might be lookin'

740
00:42:33,984 --> 00:42:36,420
for someone
over at Meecham's.

741
00:42:36,453 --> 00:42:38,155
What, did you tell her
about this already?

742
00:42:38,188 --> 00:42:40,424
No, I didn't tell her
about this already.

743
00:42:40,457 --> 00:42:41,859
I wouldn't do that.

744
00:42:42,426 --> 00:42:43,494
I'm sorry.

745
00:42:43,527 --> 00:42:45,496
You know, Jim,
this may be for the best.

746
00:42:45,529 --> 00:42:47,631
At least it's a fresh start,
you know?

747
00:42:49,633 --> 00:42:51,268
I know Bobby and Tony
will miss you,

748
00:42:51,302 --> 00:42:52,970
but they just
have to understand.

749
00:42:53,003 --> 00:42:55,806
I can't do that, Bonnie.
That boat's
all this town's got.

750
00:42:55,839 --> 00:42:56,941
Jim, what are you saying?

751
00:42:56,974 --> 00:42:59,009
You're sayin'
that this doesn't
change anything?

752
00:42:59,043 --> 00:43:00,444
(AMY CRYING)

753
00:43:09,453 --> 00:43:10,754
Why are we stoppin' here?

754
00:43:10,788 --> 00:43:12,656
Get out of the car, Jim.

755
00:43:12,690 --> 00:43:15,059
What?
Get out of the car.

756
00:43:15,092 --> 00:43:16,327
Bonnie, for cryin' out loud...

757
00:43:16,360 --> 00:43:18,429
I told you before
you had a choice, Jimmy.

758
00:43:18,462 --> 00:43:20,998
It's pretty clear to me
you've already made it.

759
00:43:22,833 --> 00:43:24,134
Go!

760
00:43:24,902 --> 00:43:26,570
Okay.

761
00:43:34,611 --> 00:43:35,879
(PHONE RINGING)

762
00:43:36,847 --> 00:43:38,248
Phone's ringing.

763
00:43:38,282 --> 00:43:39,550
I know.

764
00:43:45,322 --> 00:43:46,657
(PHONE RINGING)

765
00:44:02,039 --> 00:44:04,675
(MUSIC PLAYING
ON CAR STEREO)

766
00:44:11,315 --> 00:44:14,184
Cliffsboro! This is the place
with the Putt-Putt course

767
00:44:14,218 --> 00:44:16,353
and the cool old stores
with homemade taffy!

768
00:44:16,387 --> 00:44:18,822
Well, we're just
stopping for gas.
Batting cages!

769
00:44:18,856 --> 00:44:20,090
(GROANING)

770
00:44:20,124 --> 00:44:22,726
No, I'm sorry.
We're an hour
from Grandma's, Mike.

771
00:44:22,760 --> 00:44:24,361
You know what a mob scene
those places were

772
00:44:24,395 --> 00:44:25,763
the last time
we came through here.

773
00:44:25,796 --> 00:44:26,997
(SONG PLAYING ON CAR STEREO)

774
00:44:27,031 --> 00:44:29,266
♪ And a pocket
full of dreams

775
00:44:31,368 --> 00:44:34,738
♪ The big folks
came to town

776
00:44:34,772 --> 00:44:38,075
♪ I love that
thunderin' sound ♪

777
00:44:39,343 --> 00:44:41,945
Will you just
fill it up for me, please?
Yes, ma'am.

778
00:45:21,952 --> 00:45:23,020
Oh.

779
00:45:25,089 --> 00:45:26,890
Get back in the car, sweetie.

780
00:45:29,927 --> 00:45:31,528
Seven-sixteenth, okay?

781
00:45:31,562 --> 00:45:34,264
Seven-sixteenth?
I'm sorry.

782
00:45:35,132 --> 00:45:36,700
Travis!
I'm sorry.

783
00:45:36,734 --> 00:45:38,102
Travis, would you watch
where you're goin'?

784
00:45:38,135 --> 00:45:39,703
That could
really hurt somebody.

785
00:45:42,806 --> 00:45:44,942
I... I think I might
go to Shipley's

786
00:45:44,975 --> 00:45:46,910
and get me some coffee
or somethin'.

787
00:45:49,980 --> 00:45:51,215
What?

788
00:45:52,649 --> 00:45:54,151
Honey?

789
00:45:55,552 --> 00:45:56,820
Bonnie?

790
00:45:59,423 --> 00:46:00,958
(CRICKETS CHIRPING)

791
00:46:04,394 --> 00:46:06,730
Y'all on lunch break?

792
00:46:07,831 --> 00:46:09,633
It's beyond repair.

793
00:46:10,501 --> 00:46:12,436
Long night
in front of us, then.

794
00:46:12,469 --> 00:46:14,538
It's already
been a long night.

795
00:46:14,571 --> 00:46:17,641
TONY: Nothin' more
we can do. It's totalled.

796
00:46:17,674 --> 00:46:19,543
We need boat builders,
not mechanics.

797
00:46:19,576 --> 00:46:21,445
Well, I'll just find
somebody who can fix it.

798
00:46:21,478 --> 00:46:23,313
I already called someone.

799
00:46:23,347 --> 00:46:24,982
TONY: Staudacher
up in Michigan.

800
00:46:25,015 --> 00:46:28,051
$6,000, four weeks at least.

801
00:46:28,085 --> 00:46:30,254
Then I'll get Peter
or somebody to work on it.

802
00:46:30,287 --> 00:46:32,923
Jim, you're not listenin'
to me. It's destroyed.

803
00:46:32,956 --> 00:46:35,893
Don't tell me
I ain't listenin'.

804
00:46:35,926 --> 00:46:38,095
After all we've been
through to get this far

805
00:46:38,128 --> 00:46:39,496
and you're ready
to just throw it away.

806
00:46:39,530 --> 00:46:43,000
Why don't you just get off
your high horse, McCormick?

807
00:46:44,434 --> 00:46:45,969
It's just a damn boat.

808
00:46:47,671 --> 00:46:49,540
If that's the way
you feel about it,

809
00:46:49,573 --> 00:46:50,841
then maybe
you should have taken

810
00:46:50,874 --> 00:46:54,044
that great, fancy,
high-class job
up in Cincinnati.

811
00:46:57,481 --> 00:46:59,049
Maybe I should have.

812
00:47:03,520 --> 00:47:06,223
You've had a rough
couple of days, Jimmy.

813
00:47:06,256 --> 00:47:08,959
I think maybe
we all ought to get
a little sleep.

814
00:47:19,169 --> 00:47:20,904
(FOOTSTEPS PATTERING)

815
00:47:26,877 --> 00:47:28,679
(SCOFFS)
Mmm.

816
00:47:29,613 --> 00:47:32,349
(INHALING)

817
00:47:32,382 --> 00:47:35,619
There's a reason
they call them
"the good old days."

818
00:47:35,652 --> 00:47:36,920
What a time.

819
00:47:39,790 --> 00:47:41,825
Goin' every weekend
from race to race,

820
00:47:41,858 --> 00:47:44,595
with Davy and Linda
and everybody.

821
00:47:44,628 --> 00:47:47,231
It seemed
like such an adventure
for a while.

822
00:47:47,664 --> 00:47:49,366
(BONNIE SIGHING)

823
00:47:52,736 --> 00:47:53,971
Stupid.

824
00:47:56,807 --> 00:48:00,244
Soon it was races on Sundays,
funerals on Tuesdays.

825
00:48:02,713 --> 00:48:06,717
Sometimes a man
we barely knew,
sometimes a friend.

826
00:48:10,754 --> 00:48:11,888
And Davy.

827
00:48:13,890 --> 00:48:16,059
It's still in his blood,
isn't it?

828
00:48:24,568 --> 00:48:25,969
Good night, sweetheart.

829
00:48:26,003 --> 00:48:27,271
Good night, Mom.

830
00:49:05,609 --> 00:49:08,312
Your public servant,
available at all hours...

831
00:49:08,345 --> 00:49:09,780
Mayor,

832
00:49:11,348 --> 00:49:14,451
tomorrow's the deadline
for coverin'
the check, and...

833
00:49:14,484 --> 00:49:15,919
Well, we weren't
even close.

834
00:49:15,952 --> 00:49:18,221
Here's about
$12,000 in there.

835
00:49:19,556 --> 00:49:20,924
I'm sorry.

836
00:49:22,292 --> 00:49:23,660
Come on in, Jim.

837
00:49:24,494 --> 00:49:26,296
I'll make you a Black Cow.

838
00:49:29,733 --> 00:49:33,203
As far as the boat goes,
we're done for the season.

839
00:49:33,236 --> 00:49:35,372
Probably for good.

840
00:49:35,405 --> 00:49:37,674
I take full responsibility
for that.

841
00:49:38,608 --> 00:49:40,110
(SIGHING)

842
00:49:41,712 --> 00:49:43,280
Sure is calm tonight.

843
00:49:45,215 --> 00:49:47,451
Yeah, the plain fact is
that if it hadn't been

844
00:49:47,484 --> 00:49:50,420
for a couple
of misguided Indians,

845
00:49:50,454 --> 00:49:52,356
none of us would
be here anyway.

846
00:49:53,690 --> 00:49:57,728
Supposedly
they were paddling
upstream from Kentucky

847
00:49:57,761 --> 00:50:01,565
and they settled here
because they thought
they were in Cincinnati.

848
00:50:03,767 --> 00:50:07,938
Next thing you know,
we're the busiest port
outside New Orleans,

849
00:50:07,971 --> 00:50:10,507
wealthiest town
in the state.

850
00:50:10,540 --> 00:50:11,975
I remember
when I was a little boy,

851
00:50:12,008 --> 00:50:14,811
my dad and I
used to sit down there
on the shore

852
00:50:14,845 --> 00:50:17,781
and count all the boats
comin' in
and out of the port.

853
00:50:19,983 --> 00:50:23,286
Everybody
nowadays will tell you
they saw it comin',

854
00:50:23,320 --> 00:50:25,288
but back then,

855
00:50:25,322 --> 00:50:28,158
nobody could ever imagine
what this river
would look like

856
00:50:28,191 --> 00:50:31,294
without all those boats
goin' up and down.

857
00:50:33,163 --> 00:50:37,134
Maybe those Indians
should have built this town
on a superhighway.

858
00:50:38,602 --> 00:50:40,971
I guess we should've realized
it was only a matter of time

859
00:50:41,004 --> 00:50:43,440
before boat racin'
outgrew us, too.

860
00:50:48,979 --> 00:50:50,647
I'm sorry
for wakin' you up.

861
00:50:51,648 --> 00:50:53,350
You didn't wake me up.

862
00:51:54,511 --> 00:51:56,346
(PAPER RUSTLING)

863
00:52:15,065 --> 00:52:17,067
(THUNDER RUMBLING)

864
00:52:41,324 --> 00:52:42,459
(CAR DOOR CLOSING)

865
00:53:30,874 --> 00:53:32,375
MIKE: Well,
for those 24 hours,

866
00:53:32,409 --> 00:53:35,745
it seemed like
every person in town
came to the team's aid.

867
00:54:04,708 --> 00:54:07,544
Now, it's Tuesday,
and I want to talk to Gertie.

868
00:54:07,577 --> 00:54:08,912
SECRETARY:
I'm sorry, Mr. Wallin.

869
00:54:08,945 --> 00:54:11,514
She had to run
to her grandson's
piano recital.

870
00:54:11,548 --> 00:54:13,617
Oh, this is ridiculous.
Get me the bank president.

871
00:54:13,650 --> 00:54:15,251
He's at the recital also.

872
00:54:15,285 --> 00:54:17,153
Who is this kid,
Vladimir Horowitz?

873
00:54:17,187 --> 00:54:19,289
No, sir,
Ritchie McCallister.

874
00:54:19,322 --> 00:54:22,659
There are no Vladimirs
in Madison,
as far as I know.

875
00:54:23,293 --> 00:54:24,661
Have a nice day.

876
00:54:27,464 --> 00:54:29,265
(RAIN PATTERING)

877
00:54:33,236 --> 00:54:36,640
Darlene, you think
they'd let an old fat guy
be an astronaut?

878
00:54:36,673 --> 00:54:39,109
Sir?

879
00:54:39,142 --> 00:54:41,745
If I do somethin' stupid
and get
voted out of office,

880
00:54:41,778 --> 00:54:43,947
I'd have to come up
with somethin' else,
right?

881
00:54:43,980 --> 00:54:45,015
(CHUCKLES)

882
00:54:45,915 --> 00:54:47,017
Hello?

883
00:54:48,385 --> 00:54:49,986
Hello?

884
00:54:50,020 --> 00:54:51,721
Oh, afternoon,
Miss McCormick.

885
00:54:51,755 --> 00:54:52,856
Hi.

886
00:54:52,889 --> 00:54:55,125
I hope you don't mind
we come back here.

887
00:54:55,158 --> 00:54:58,361
Well,
we heard from some folks
down there at Shipley's

888
00:54:58,395 --> 00:55:01,131
that Jim wasn't gonna
be able to finish this,
due to the boat and all.

889
00:55:01,164 --> 00:55:02,499
So he doesn't know
you're here?

890
00:55:02,932 --> 00:55:04,834
No, ma'am.

891
00:55:04,868 --> 00:55:07,704
Well, let me get you guys
some pop or something.

892
00:55:08,538 --> 00:55:10,006
This boat's
gonna be in the water

893
00:55:10,040 --> 00:55:11,875
wherever the heck
the Gold Cup is.

894
00:55:12,776 --> 00:55:14,377
TONY: Hey, Jimbo!
Yeah?

895
00:55:14,411 --> 00:55:15,845
You got a phone call here.

896
00:55:15,879 --> 00:55:17,647
It's Jake Merrill
over at the bank.

897
00:55:17,681 --> 00:55:18,715
Uh-oh.

898
00:55:22,285 --> 00:55:23,420
(SIGHING)

899
00:55:26,690 --> 00:55:28,058
Hey, Jake.

900
00:55:28,091 --> 00:55:29,926
JAKE: Hey, Jim,
have you talked
to the Mayor?

901
00:55:29,959 --> 00:55:32,562
Yeah,
I talked to him last night.
I was at his house.

902
00:55:32,595 --> 00:55:34,764
So you know
he covered the check.

903
00:55:35,565 --> 00:55:38,201
What?
The $50,000.

904
00:55:38,234 --> 00:55:41,504
He did what?
Yeah, from the city's
sanitation funds.

905
00:55:41,538 --> 00:55:43,106
(STUTTERS)

906
00:55:43,139 --> 00:55:45,408
Listen, I gotta go.
I gotta... I gotta
get to the ticket office.

907
00:55:45,442 --> 00:55:46,910
Okay, bye.
Okay, Jim.

908
00:55:49,412 --> 00:55:51,748
Tony!
Call this guy
Buddy Johnson.

909
00:55:51,781 --> 00:55:53,750
See if he's available
to race for us.

910
00:55:53,783 --> 00:55:55,518
What for?
We got the Gold Cup.

911
00:55:55,552 --> 00:55:57,120
What? We what?
We got the Gold Cup.

912
00:55:57,153 --> 00:55:59,956
We may not have
our garbage collected
for the next three years...

913
00:55:59,989 --> 00:56:02,025
but we got the Gold Cup!

914
00:56:02,058 --> 00:56:03,126
(LAUGHING)
We got it!

915
00:56:03,159 --> 00:56:04,761
Let's go call him!

916
00:56:04,794 --> 00:56:08,231
SECRETARY:
Good morning.
Madison Bank and Trust.

917
00:56:08,264 --> 00:56:11,101
(BABY PLEASE DON'T GO
PLAYING)

918
00:56:13,636 --> 00:56:16,473
♪ Baby, please don't go

919
00:56:16,506 --> 00:56:18,908
You're gonna have
to rebuild the sponson

920
00:56:18,942 --> 00:56:20,477
and take it all the way
back to the stringers.

921
00:56:20,510 --> 00:56:21,745
♪ Down to New Orleans

922
00:56:21,778 --> 00:56:24,581
♪ You know I love you so,
Baby, please don't go

923
00:56:26,082 --> 00:56:27,117
♪ All right

924
00:56:28,084 --> 00:56:30,086
♪ Before I be your dog

925
00:56:30,120 --> 00:56:32,055
MAN ON RADIO:
One-Bravo-Delta,
you have a call.

926
00:56:32,088 --> 00:56:33,490
One-Bravo-Delta.

927
00:56:33,523 --> 00:56:34,791
♪ Be your dog

928
00:56:34,824 --> 00:56:37,494
Come on, Harry,
I know
you're out there.

929
00:56:37,527 --> 00:56:39,562
♪ Baby, please don't go

930
00:56:40,830 --> 00:56:41,865
♪ All right

931
00:56:42,632 --> 00:56:44,601
♪ When your man done gone

932
00:56:45,668 --> 00:56:48,838
♪ When the man done gone

933
00:56:48,872 --> 00:56:51,407
♪ When the man done gone,
at the county farm

934
00:56:51,441 --> 00:56:52,675
Let's do it!

935
00:56:52,709 --> 00:56:54,344
♪ Baby, please don't go

936
00:56:55,645 --> 00:56:56,679
♪ All right

937
00:56:57,380 --> 00:56:59,015
♪ Oh, hit it

938
00:57:04,854 --> 00:57:05,889
♪ Hey

939
00:57:08,591 --> 00:57:11,361
(MOTORBOAT HUMMING)

940
00:57:17,033 --> 00:57:18,535
BOBBY: It floats!

941
00:57:18,568 --> 00:57:20,370
(CROWD CHEERING)

942
00:57:20,403 --> 00:57:21,638
CROWD: Yeah!

943
00:57:21,671 --> 00:57:23,206
(MAN WHISTLING)
BOBBY: It floats!

944
00:57:23,239 --> 00:57:25,241
(MAN WHOOPING)

945
00:57:25,675 --> 00:57:26,776
Yeah!

946
00:57:28,244 --> 00:57:31,114
Excuse me.
What's going on?

947
00:57:31,147 --> 00:57:33,349
Oh, it floats.
Isn't that great?

948
00:57:35,051 --> 00:57:37,720
Hey, you're Buddy.
In the flesh. Mr. McCormick!

949
00:57:37,754 --> 00:57:40,156
Oh, God, I'm sorry.
We were just
testing the boat out here.

950
00:57:40,190 --> 00:57:43,026
Well... Here,
meet my wife Bonnie.
And it's Jim, by the way.

951
00:57:43,059 --> 00:57:45,829
How are you?
This is my new bride Tami.
Newlyweds. Congratulations.

952
00:57:45,862 --> 00:57:47,297
Thanks. Six weeks.

953
00:57:47,330 --> 00:57:49,866
Well, come on, Buddy,
let me introduce you
to the
Miss Madison.

954
00:57:49,899 --> 00:57:52,268
Oh, she is an angel.

955
00:57:52,302 --> 00:57:55,772
So I hear you're gonna be
driving for Atlas Van Lines
in Dayton this weekend.

956
00:57:55,805 --> 00:57:57,106
Yeah, they only
need me for one race,

957
00:57:57,140 --> 00:57:59,843
so I'll be available
for the Gold Cup. Well,

958
00:57:59,876 --> 00:58:01,744
Atlas is a damn
fine operation.

959
00:58:01,778 --> 00:58:04,113
You're gonna
have some excellent
equipment underneath you.

960
00:58:04,147 --> 00:58:05,548
Yeah, I can't hardly wait.

961
00:58:05,582 --> 00:58:08,518
Well, let... Let me
just tell you a little
bit about this boat.

962
00:58:08,551 --> 00:58:10,787
Go ahead and
hop in there, Buddy.

963
00:58:10,820 --> 00:58:12,188
(STUTTERS)

964
00:58:12,222 --> 00:58:13,656
she's 12 years old,

965
00:58:13,690 --> 00:58:16,025
she's heavy
and she's gonna handle
a whole lot different

966
00:58:16,059 --> 00:58:18,127
than anything
you've ever piloted.

967
00:58:18,161 --> 00:58:20,496
I... I'm just telling you,
'cause we just rebuilt

968
00:58:20,530 --> 00:58:21,898
the whole right sponson
on her.

969
00:58:21,931 --> 00:58:24,234
The engine is down
on horsepower. And...

970
00:58:24,267 --> 00:58:28,338
Well, frankly,
Buddy, we really don't know
what she's got left in her.

971
00:58:28,371 --> 00:58:30,807
I'll tell you what, Jim.

972
00:58:30,840 --> 00:58:32,208
As long as she floats
and her engine runs,

973
00:58:32,242 --> 00:58:34,277
I'll put her
at the front of the pack.

974
00:58:34,310 --> 00:58:35,812
Supper was great.
Thanks again. Oh.

975
00:58:35,845 --> 00:58:37,647
You're welcome.
I'm glad you could come.

976
00:58:37,680 --> 00:58:39,949
Good luck on the
Atlas.
See you Tuesday?
Yeah.

977
00:58:39,983 --> 00:58:42,785
Great. See you next week.
Oh, you betcha, boss.

978
00:58:42,819 --> 00:58:44,020
Drive safely.
Thanks.

979
00:58:44,053 --> 00:58:45,455
Thanks.
Bye.

980
00:58:48,024 --> 00:58:49,392
BUDDY: Hey, come here.

981
00:58:49,425 --> 00:58:50,493
(TAMI GIGGLING)

982
00:58:50,526 --> 00:58:52,095
(BUDDY WHOOPING)

983
00:58:53,396 --> 00:58:55,732
JIM: Oh, he's a stick
of dynamite.

984
00:58:55,765 --> 00:58:57,934
Years ago I knew
a guy like that.

985
00:58:59,369 --> 00:59:01,905
Well, let's see
if I can still try here.

986
00:59:01,938 --> 00:59:03,273
(GRUNTING)

987
00:59:03,306 --> 00:59:04,607
(LAUGHING)
It's not funny.

988
00:59:04,641 --> 00:59:05,808
I hurt my back!

989
00:59:05,842 --> 00:59:08,411
MIKE: With a new driver
and restored boat,

990
00:59:08,444 --> 00:59:10,680
the mood in the town was high.

991
00:59:10,713 --> 00:59:13,283
But things were different
with me

992
00:59:13,316 --> 00:59:16,319
and none of that
seemed to matter anymore.

993
00:59:16,352 --> 00:59:19,389
(BIRDS TWITTERING)

994
00:59:19,422 --> 00:59:21,858
MALE ANNOUNCER ON TV:
Making his first appearance
here in Dayton,

995
00:59:21,891 --> 00:59:25,395
is Limited class driver
Buddy Johnson
in the Atlas Van Lines boat.

996
00:59:25,428 --> 00:59:27,196
(PHONE RINGING)
Although he's driving
for Atlas today,

997
00:59:27,230 --> 00:59:29,432
Buddy will be the driver
for the Madison team

998
00:59:29,465 --> 00:59:31,134
at next week's
Gold Cup Championship race.

999
00:59:31,167 --> 00:59:32,669
BONNIE: Madison Regatta
ticket office.

1000
00:59:32,702 --> 00:59:34,103
Hey, Audrey.
Hi, Jim.
We got the race on.

1001
00:59:34,137 --> 00:59:36,539
Great, thank you.
Hi, honey.

1002
00:59:36,572 --> 00:59:38,975
I'm okay.
How are the ticket
sales coming along?

1003
00:59:39,008 --> 00:59:41,110
It's all right.
Bit of an upswing this week,

1004
00:59:41,144 --> 00:59:43,613
but we need
a lot of walk-ups,
or we're in big trouble.

1005
00:59:43,646 --> 00:59:46,316
The final heat's startin'.
Thank you.

1006
00:59:46,349 --> 00:59:48,618
ANNOUNCER: The boats
are charging towards
the starting line

1007
00:59:48,651 --> 00:59:50,353
deck to deck...
Come on, Buddy.

1008
00:59:50,386 --> 00:59:52,255
...Budweiser
and
Cat's Pride
on the inside.

1009
00:59:52,288 --> 00:59:54,057
Which one is he?
He's right there.

1010
00:59:54,090 --> 00:59:55,692
JIM: On the outside.

1011
00:59:55,725 --> 00:59:57,660
He's racin' for Atlas
this week.

1012
00:59:57,694 --> 00:59:59,495
...is on the far outside.
Let's go.

1013
00:59:59,529 --> 01:00:01,898
They hit the start,
and the race...

1014
01:00:01,931 --> 01:00:03,166
(EXPLOSION)

1015
01:00:03,199 --> 01:00:04,267
(ALL GASPING)
ANNOUNCER: An accident!

1016
01:00:04,300 --> 01:00:06,069
My God,
an accident on the course!

1017
01:00:06,102 --> 01:00:07,804
It's the Atlas
Van Lines boat!

1018
01:00:07,837 --> 01:00:10,006
The
Atlas
has flipped
on the course!

1019
01:00:10,039 --> 01:00:11,607
It's Buddy Johnson's boat!

1020
01:00:11,641 --> 01:00:12,775
Oh, God.

1021
01:00:12,809 --> 01:00:14,911
ANNOUNCER: What a tragic
accident this will be.

1022
01:00:14,944 --> 01:00:18,481
Buddy Johnson, 22 years old,

1023
01:00:18,514 --> 01:00:21,017
and the sport's
most prominent
up-and-coming driver

1024
01:00:21,050 --> 01:00:22,652
from the Limited class,

1025
01:00:22,685 --> 01:00:26,089
seen there on the stretcher,
lifting to that helicopter.

1026
01:00:26,122 --> 01:00:29,392
Seems the rescue teams here
are on the course.

1027
01:00:29,425 --> 01:00:31,160
His young wife is looking on.

1028
01:00:31,194 --> 01:00:33,563
Oh, God,
what she must be feeling.

1029
01:00:33,596 --> 01:00:36,499
Our thoughts and our prayers
are with the family.

1030
01:00:42,538 --> 01:00:44,340
(BIRDS CAWING)

1031
01:01:48,404 --> 01:01:50,573
MALE ANNOUNCER:
And
Madison
making her move now

1032
01:01:50,606 --> 01:01:53,976
as they head down
the straightaway
into the backstretch.

1033
01:01:54,010 --> 01:01:56,646
And it's
Budweiser
still leading
the
Miss Madison,

1034
01:01:56,679 --> 01:01:59,715
followed by
the
Towne Club,
the
Thriftway,

1035
01:01:59,749 --> 01:02:02,919
with
Atlas Van Lines
way back in the pack.

1036
01:02:02,952 --> 01:02:06,923
And look at this, folks.
Davy Snyder in the
Towne Club

1037
01:02:06,956 --> 01:02:10,293
making his move,
challenging his best friend
Jim McCormick.

1038
01:02:10,326 --> 01:02:13,262
He's right on
McCormick's shoulder.

1039
01:02:13,296 --> 01:02:16,933
And it's
Budweiser
and
Madison
going for
the same lane.

1040
01:02:16,966 --> 01:02:18,801
Going for the same lane,
folks!

1041
01:02:18,835 --> 01:02:20,603
McCormick is gonna
have to drop back.

1042
01:02:20,636 --> 01:02:24,941
But no, he hits the gas pedal!
He spins out!

1043
01:02:24,974 --> 01:02:28,511
McCormick spins
out 180 degrees!

1044
01:02:28,544 --> 01:02:31,280
Here comes Davy Snyder
with
Towne Club.

1045
01:02:31,314 --> 01:02:32,849
Flips twice!

1046
01:02:32,882 --> 01:02:34,617
No!

1047
01:02:38,054 --> 01:02:41,557
And there's two drivers
face down in the water!

1048
01:03:07,783 --> 01:03:08,851
Bonnie.

1049
01:03:12,688 --> 01:03:14,524
Bonnie.
What?

1050
01:03:14,557 --> 01:03:15,758
Why did I even go up there?

1051
01:03:15,791 --> 01:03:17,460
I knew what you were doin'.

1052
01:03:17,493 --> 01:03:18,661
I owe it to them, Bonnie.

1053
01:03:18,694 --> 01:03:19,829
Who do you owe?

1054
01:03:19,862 --> 01:03:22,832
The team, the town?
Who, Buddy?

1055
01:03:22,865 --> 01:03:24,467
Buddy has nothin'
to do with this.

1056
01:03:24,500 --> 01:03:26,269
Who, then? Davy?

1057
01:03:26,302 --> 01:03:27,937
Is this your way of asking
for his forgiveness?

1058
01:03:27,970 --> 01:03:30,439
You think Davy wants
you to go out there
and kill yourself?

1059
01:03:30,473 --> 01:03:32,375
You don't owe anyone.

1060
01:03:32,408 --> 01:03:37,180
For eight years I've been
trying to explain to people
what I was thinkin'

1061
01:03:37,213 --> 01:03:40,316
when I walked away
from that cockpit
in the middle of the season,

1062
01:03:40,349 --> 01:03:43,319
and for eight years
I've been
trying to convince them

1063
01:03:43,352 --> 01:03:44,720
that it was because
of Epperson,

1064
01:03:44,754 --> 01:03:47,190
or because
of Davy's crash,
or because of you,

1065
01:03:47,223 --> 01:03:50,827
and all along I've known
it didn't have anything
to do with anybody but me.

1066
01:03:50,860 --> 01:03:52,628
Jim...
Now hold on a second.

1067
01:03:52,662 --> 01:03:54,964
Maybe I didn't have the guts
to keep racin'

1068
01:03:54,997 --> 01:03:58,000
for the same reason
that I do not have
the guts to leave here.

1069
01:03:58,034 --> 01:03:59,335
It's not fair.

1070
01:04:01,103 --> 01:04:02,505
I'm gonna do it, Bonnie.

1071
01:04:07,610 --> 01:04:10,479
(REVVING)

1072
01:04:18,221 --> 01:04:20,890
(MOTORBOAT ROARING)

1073
01:04:46,649 --> 01:04:48,584
(ENGINE SPUTTERING)

1074
01:04:52,555 --> 01:04:54,357
Oh, he stalled it.

1075
01:04:54,390 --> 01:04:56,926
(CROWD MUTTERING)

1076
01:05:11,240 --> 01:05:13,442
We got an all-practice day
tomorrow, now.

1077
01:05:13,476 --> 01:05:15,278
Oh, Lordy.
What?

1078
01:05:16,412 --> 01:05:18,748
TONY: Good grief.

1079
01:05:18,781 --> 01:05:22,551
There's no lookin' back now.
Let's go.

1080
01:05:22,585 --> 01:05:24,587
I keep waitin'
on the caboose.

1081
01:05:25,755 --> 01:05:27,957
Wait, you guys.

1082
01:05:27,990 --> 01:05:30,593
MAN ON RADIO:
One-Bravo-Delta,
this is Central Station.

1083
01:05:30,626 --> 01:05:32,928
You got another one.

1084
01:05:32,962 --> 01:05:35,698
McCormick, you know,
this is really
becoming ridiculous.

1085
01:05:35,731 --> 01:05:37,967
Harry, Harry, it's Bonnie.

1086
01:05:38,567 --> 01:05:39,869
What's wrong?

1087
01:05:39,902 --> 01:05:43,139
(STEAM WHISTLE BLOWING)

1088
01:05:43,172 --> 01:05:45,608
WOMAN ON PA:
Welcome to Madison,
Indiana, folks,

1089
01:05:45,641 --> 01:05:47,977
proud home
of the
Miss Madison team.

1090
01:05:48,010 --> 01:05:50,212
Thank you for joining us
as we host the Gold Cup

1091
01:05:50,246 --> 01:05:52,648
for the first time
in the town's history.

1092
01:05:52,682 --> 01:05:54,717
Please watch your step
as you disembark.

1093
01:05:54,750 --> 01:05:57,920
And don't forget
to buy your tickets
for the big race tomorrow.

1094
01:05:57,953 --> 01:06:01,090
You can find them
in the gold and red booths
to your right.

1095
01:06:01,123 --> 01:06:02,958
On behalf of
the
Belle of Louisville,

1096
01:06:02,992 --> 01:06:05,628
we hope you enjoy your stay
here in Madison.

1097
01:06:16,439 --> 01:06:18,107
Hey, Harry!

1098
01:06:18,140 --> 01:06:19,842
What the heck are you
doin' up here?

1099
01:06:19,875 --> 01:06:21,344
How about that, huh?

1100
01:06:21,377 --> 01:06:22,912
(JIM CHUCKLING)

1101
01:06:22,945 --> 01:06:26,148
I should have just
moved my boat up here
and retired.

1102
01:06:26,182 --> 01:06:30,019
Gotten a hell of a lot
more fishin' in,
I'll tell you that.

1103
01:06:35,691 --> 01:06:37,526
Don't we call that
dirt, son?

1104
01:06:37,560 --> 01:06:40,029
HARRY: You're gonna have
to re-wash
every one of these.

1105
01:06:40,062 --> 01:06:42,965
Okay.
No, no, not okay.

1106
01:06:42,998 --> 01:06:45,701
Do it.
Okay. I mean...

1107
01:06:45,735 --> 01:06:47,870
Mr. Volpi, it's a pleasure.
Hello, sir. How are you?

1108
01:06:47,903 --> 01:06:50,039
Tony Steinhardt.
You can call me Harry, Tony.

1109
01:06:50,072 --> 01:06:52,441
You got it.
I was goin' over
this blower assembly.

1110
01:06:52,475 --> 01:06:56,045
I'll tell you right off,
you're gonna wanna re-check
the clearance on this one.

1111
01:06:56,078 --> 01:06:58,614
Will do.
Good attitude. I like it.

1112
01:06:58,647 --> 01:07:01,283
Roberto.
A face from the past.

1113
01:07:01,317 --> 01:07:02,818
Been a long time, Harry.

1114
01:07:02,852 --> 01:07:03,919
Sure has.

1115
01:07:03,953 --> 01:07:05,287
That's lookin' real good.

1116
01:07:05,321 --> 01:07:06,655
Damn right it does.

1117
01:07:06,689 --> 01:07:07,923
Atta boy.

1118
01:07:07,957 --> 01:07:10,259
Harry, about
the nitrous system...

1119
01:07:10,292 --> 01:07:13,996
No, no. No nitrous now, son.
It's out of the question.

1120
01:07:14,029 --> 01:07:16,332
You're gonna
wanna disassemble
this entire engine

1121
01:07:16,365 --> 01:07:18,801
while I go out
and find myself
something to eat.

1122
01:07:18,834 --> 01:07:20,936
I'll be back
in an hour or two.

1123
01:07:20,970 --> 01:07:24,240
I don't know
how you heard, Harry,
but thanks.

1124
01:07:25,174 --> 01:07:26,742
I got a hunch you do.

1125
01:07:34,984 --> 01:07:38,988
You know the first thing
the big fish
tell the little baby fish?

1126
01:07:41,257 --> 01:07:44,560
"Don't ever eat anything
hanging on a string
off a dock."

1127
01:07:47,496 --> 01:07:48,898
Let's go fishing.

1128
01:08:04,447 --> 01:08:06,015
Let me see you cast.

1129
01:08:10,119 --> 01:08:13,189
Atta boy.
The man can cast.

1130
01:08:16,091 --> 01:08:20,396
Haven't been
helping your dad out
too much lately, have you?

1131
01:08:20,429 --> 01:08:23,265
What's it gonna matter?
People will
still laugh at us.

1132
01:08:23,299 --> 01:08:26,869
People? You mean the people
on the other teams?

1133
01:08:26,902 --> 01:08:29,738
It would be nice,
wouldn't it if we could

1134
01:08:29,772 --> 01:08:31,774
change places
with other people.

1135
01:08:31,807 --> 01:08:35,611
You know, kind of
wake up one day and
live in a different place,

1136
01:08:35,644 --> 01:08:39,181
big house and fancy parents.

1137
01:08:39,215 --> 01:08:40,783
That'd really be swell,
wouldn't it?

1138
01:08:40,816 --> 01:08:42,351
We wouldn't lose anymore.

1139
01:08:42,384 --> 01:08:45,387
No, and you
wouldn't have to work at it
anymore, either, would you?

1140
01:08:45,421 --> 01:08:46,889
No.

1141
01:08:46,922 --> 01:08:50,025
Do you think
your dad and the team
would like it that way?

1142
01:08:50,059 --> 01:08:53,729
There's nobody
that works harder
at this game

1143
01:08:53,762 --> 01:08:56,031
than the boys
in that garage.

1144
01:08:57,066 --> 01:08:58,534
Then we should be winning.

1145
01:08:58,567 --> 01:09:01,637
Well, yes, sir,
I guess we should.

1146
01:09:01,670 --> 01:09:05,574
But every now and then,
a pocketful of money

1147
01:09:05,608 --> 01:09:08,344
will whoop the pants
out of plain old hard work.

1148
01:09:08,377 --> 01:09:09,578
(FISHING LINE WHIRRING)

1149
01:09:09,612 --> 01:09:11,947
You got somethin'.
Pull on her.

1150
01:09:11,981 --> 01:09:13,949
Atta boy.
You're a fisherman!

1151
01:09:13,983 --> 01:09:15,551
You're a fisherman!

1152
01:09:16,819 --> 01:09:18,787
MAN ON RADIO:
It's 10:48, WMAD,

1153
01:09:18,821 --> 01:09:21,156
ten hours to go before
our own Jim McCormick...

1154
01:09:21,190 --> 01:09:23,826
climbs in the
Miss Madison
to race for the Gold Cup.

1155
01:09:23,859 --> 01:09:25,494
Hey, Jim.
Yeah?

1156
01:09:25,528 --> 01:09:28,497
You wanna go out to my truck
and get the socket wrench?

1157
01:09:28,531 --> 01:09:29,632
Sure.

1158
01:09:38,474 --> 01:09:40,175
Wait a minute.
Your truck?

1159
01:09:40,209 --> 01:09:41,710
You didn't drive your truck.

1160
01:09:42,611 --> 01:09:44,013
Now, if you weren't
so damn tired,

1161
01:09:44,046 --> 01:09:46,182
you'd have figured that out
before you even
went out there.

1162
01:09:46,215 --> 01:09:48,617
Come on, Harry,
you're shorthanded
as it is.

1163
01:09:48,651 --> 01:09:50,953
We got 10 hours
to get that engine
runnin' right.

1164
01:09:50,986 --> 01:09:52,388
Go to sleep!

1165
01:09:53,989 --> 01:09:55,624
All right, well, I'm goin'.

1166
01:09:55,658 --> 01:09:58,861
I got that breather hose
off the accessory housing.

1167
01:09:58,894 --> 01:10:01,196
So, where do we go next?

1168
01:10:01,230 --> 01:10:02,831
Next page.

1169
01:10:02,865 --> 01:10:04,867
(POUNDING ON DOOR)

1170
01:10:04,900 --> 01:10:05,935
(SIGHING)

1171
01:10:05,968 --> 01:10:07,002
(CHUCKLING)

1172
01:10:07,036 --> 01:10:08,304
(HARRY MUTTERING)

1173
01:10:08,337 --> 01:10:12,107
McCormick,
I told you to go home
and get some sleep.

1174
01:10:24,153 --> 01:10:25,921
(CRICKETS CHIRPING)

1175
01:10:26,755 --> 01:10:28,223
MAYOR: Hey, Jimbo!

1176
01:10:30,726 --> 01:10:32,494
Big day for you tomorrow.

1177
01:10:33,662 --> 01:10:35,231
Big day for all of us.

1178
01:10:35,264 --> 01:10:38,200
Listen, Jimmy,
don't worry too much
about the race.

1179
01:10:38,233 --> 01:10:41,971
Just coax her
through a couple of laps,
we'll all be proud.

1180
01:10:42,504 --> 01:10:43,939
See you tomorrow.

1181
01:10:53,249 --> 01:10:55,351
(METALLIC CLANKING)

1182
01:10:55,384 --> 01:10:58,053
HARRY: I see why
this nitrous system
ain't gonna work.

1183
01:10:58,087 --> 01:11:00,222
Your motor just
plumb wore out.

1184
01:11:00,255 --> 01:11:02,558
Half these parts
are shot.

1185
01:11:02,591 --> 01:11:04,927
Maybe we should
get some new ones.

1186
01:11:04,960 --> 01:11:08,097
There aren't many
World War II airplane
engines available

1187
01:11:08,130 --> 01:11:10,032
in southern Indiana
at this hour.

1188
01:11:10,065 --> 01:11:12,568
Hey, maybe we ought to
drive to Columbus
and steal the engine

1189
01:11:12,601 --> 01:11:15,537
from that old fighter plane
in front of City Hall.

1190
01:11:17,539 --> 01:11:19,074
Now, hold on a second here.

1191
01:11:19,108 --> 01:11:20,242
I'll do it.

1192
01:11:20,276 --> 01:11:21,844
I'm in.

1193
01:11:21,877 --> 01:11:25,848
Fellows, even if there
is still an engine in it,
which there probably isn't,

1194
01:11:25,881 --> 01:11:27,683
we're talkin' about
a plane on display

1195
01:11:27,716 --> 01:11:30,019
down in front
of their City Hall.

1196
01:11:30,052 --> 01:11:34,089
As in the mayor's office,
the county jail.

1197
01:11:34,123 --> 01:11:37,092
I don't think
there's much left here
to discuss. Do you?

1198
01:11:37,126 --> 01:11:38,661
We can take my truck.

1199
01:11:39,995 --> 01:11:41,764
Wait, I was just kiddin'.

1200
01:11:42,998 --> 01:11:44,199
(SIGHING)

1201
01:11:44,233 --> 01:11:46,402
Please don't look at me
like that.

1202
01:11:47,436 --> 01:11:49,505
You wanna do old Harry
a favor?

1203
01:11:50,606 --> 01:11:51,974
Go home
and get some sleep.

1204
01:11:52,007 --> 01:11:54,309
I need you in the morning
to be sharp.

1205
01:12:12,327 --> 01:12:15,297
BOBBY: Maybe we
should come back
tomorrow around noon.

1206
01:12:15,330 --> 01:12:16,932
Won't be as bright.

1207
01:12:21,103 --> 01:12:22,838
Here. No, let me have that.
Okay.

1208
01:12:22,871 --> 01:12:24,540
We're on it.
It's okay.

1209
01:12:26,175 --> 01:12:28,010
(DOG BARKING)

1210
01:12:32,114 --> 01:12:33,849
What have you got there?

1211
01:12:33,882 --> 01:12:35,084
(GRUNTING)

1212
01:12:35,117 --> 01:12:36,585
It's the tach drive.

1213
01:12:36,618 --> 01:12:39,421
You got it?
I can't get in there.

1214
01:12:39,455 --> 01:12:41,023
(GRUNTING) Now if we just...

1215
01:12:43,125 --> 01:12:45,227
had somebody with smaller...

1216
01:12:45,260 --> 01:12:46,762
Hands?

1217
01:12:48,464 --> 01:12:50,265
HARRY: Well, I'll be.

1218
01:13:39,581 --> 01:13:41,216
(BIRDS CHIRPING)

1219
01:14:40,108 --> 01:14:41,610
Go get them, Jimmy.

1220
01:15:11,573 --> 01:15:13,475
It's just like in
Huckleberry Finn.

1221
01:15:13,508 --> 01:15:15,644
Look at the smoke
coming out of those stacks!

1222
01:15:15,677 --> 01:15:17,779
That's not smoke,
that's steam.

1223
01:15:17,813 --> 01:15:18,947
GIRL: Wow!

1224
01:15:18,981 --> 01:15:20,449
Have you ever been on it?

1225
01:15:20,482 --> 01:15:21,950
Sure, loads of times.

1226
01:15:21,984 --> 01:15:24,419
They're givin' rides all day.
I can get you on if you want.

1227
01:15:24,453 --> 01:15:27,222
Cool!
Let's go.

1228
01:15:27,256 --> 01:15:31,760
Wait! My dad said we could
watch TV in his
new motor home. Guys?

1229
01:15:31,793 --> 01:15:34,329
(STEAM WHISTLE BLOWING)

1230
01:15:36,598 --> 01:15:40,602
Hey, Jim!
Jim, I hear you guys
only sold 30,000 tickets.

1231
01:15:40,636 --> 01:15:43,105
Well, George,
we're countin'
on a few walk-ups.

1232
01:15:43,138 --> 01:15:46,842
What is ABC gonna say
when they see
a half-empty shoreline?

1233
01:15:46,875 --> 01:15:48,644
I suppose we'll find out.

1234
01:15:49,544 --> 01:15:52,214
I knew this was a mistake.

1235
01:15:52,247 --> 01:15:53,982
Who'd ever want
to come to this place?

1236
01:15:59,054 --> 01:16:01,356
KEITH: The banks
of the Ohio River as it flows

1237
01:16:01,390 --> 01:16:03,425
by the city of Madison,
Indiana,

1238
01:16:03,458 --> 01:16:06,995
population about 13,000
on a hot summer day.

1239
01:16:07,029 --> 01:16:10,432
It's the setting today
with more than 100,000 people

1240
01:16:10,465 --> 01:16:14,870
to watch the Gold Cup race
for Unlimited hydroplanes.

1241
01:16:14,903 --> 01:16:18,373
It's an American
folklore festival
where thousands and thousands

1242
01:16:18,407 --> 01:16:21,610
have come to enjoy themselves
and just have some fun.

1243
01:16:21,643 --> 01:16:23,145
Hello, I'm Keith Jackson

1244
01:16:23,178 --> 01:16:25,948
and you're about to see today
on ABC's
Wide World of Sports

1245
01:16:25,981 --> 01:16:29,518
what we call the thunderboats,
the Unlimited hydroplanes,

1246
01:16:29,551 --> 01:16:34,056
the powerhouses
of boat racing,
run for the Gold Cup.

1247
01:16:34,089 --> 01:16:36,959
This is the Grand Prix
for the Unlimited hydroplanes.

1248
01:16:36,992 --> 01:16:40,028
This is the one
that every man in boat racing
strives to win

1249
01:16:40,062 --> 01:16:44,232
at one time or another,
because this is the top prize.

1250
01:16:44,266 --> 01:16:46,935
(ENGINES REVVING)

1251
01:16:57,479 --> 01:17:00,816
The boats are now
moving onto the course.

1252
01:17:00,849 --> 01:17:03,852
As you fans know,
the race is set up
on a points system.

1253
01:17:03,885 --> 01:17:07,389
They'll run five heats today,
and the five boats
with the most points...

1254
01:17:07,422 --> 01:17:10,325
will advance
to the winner-take-all final.

1255
01:17:10,359 --> 01:17:13,929
The heavy favorite today
is Rick Winston
in
Miss Budweiser.

1256
01:17:13,962 --> 01:17:16,898
He's gunning for his third
straight Gold Cup trophy

1257
01:17:16,932 --> 01:17:22,270
and he's piloted his boat
to four wins in five races
so far this year.

1258
01:17:34,383 --> 01:17:35,417
(FIRING)

1259
01:17:37,319 --> 01:17:40,589
(HYDROPLANES ROARING)

1260
01:17:49,831 --> 01:17:54,036
Coming down the straightaway,
it's deck to deck to deck
across the field,

1261
01:17:54,069 --> 01:17:55,771
all five boats even.

1262
01:17:55,804 --> 01:17:59,241
It looks like
Cat's Pride
will hold the inside lane.

1263
01:18:02,411 --> 01:18:06,581
The leader,
Cat's Pride,
spinning out in turn two
and stalls.

1264
01:18:06,615 --> 01:18:10,919
And here's
Miss Madison,
coming out of the pack
and taking the lead.

1265
01:18:10,952 --> 01:18:14,222
(ALL CHEERING)
Jim McCormick, in his first
race in eight years,

1266
01:18:14,256 --> 01:18:16,491
has taken the lead.

1267
01:18:29,104 --> 01:18:31,873
And here comes Rick Winston
in the
Budweiser.

1268
01:18:40,449 --> 01:18:43,351
Here's the
Budweiser
cutting in front
of the
Madison,

1269
01:18:43,385 --> 01:18:44,920
taking the inside lane.

1270
01:18:44,953 --> 01:18:47,756
Jim McCormick is caught
in the
Bud's
rooster tail.

1271
01:18:47,789 --> 01:18:51,126
Hey, now that's a wash-down!

1272
01:18:51,159 --> 01:18:55,263
Boy, Rick Winston
was dangerously close
to a penalty on that move.

1273
01:18:56,865 --> 01:18:58,500
Now McCormick
has more trouble.

1274
01:18:58,533 --> 01:19:00,068
Here comes the
Atlas.

1275
01:19:03,672 --> 01:19:05,373
No!

1276
01:19:05,407 --> 01:19:07,742
Now the
Notre Dame
is after him.

1277
01:19:11,146 --> 01:19:14,549
This is critical.
The winner of this duel
takes third place

1278
01:19:14,583 --> 01:19:17,819
and gets enough points
to make it to the next heat.
Come on, baby!

1279
01:19:28,463 --> 01:19:34,102
Coming to the finish line,
it's
Budweiser,
it's
Atlas...

1280
01:19:34,136 --> 01:19:38,306
Madison
taking third,
advancing to the next heat.

1281
01:19:39,708 --> 01:19:43,178
(ALL CHEERING)
And the home folks
are loving it!

1282
01:19:53,488 --> 01:19:54,589
JIM: Winston!

1283
01:19:56,491 --> 01:19:58,727
That wash-down
was no accident,
and you know it!

1284
01:19:58,760 --> 01:20:00,562
TONY: Jimmy, come on now,
he's not worth it.

1285
01:20:00,595 --> 01:20:02,531
You know what they say,
McCormick, that's racing.

1286
01:20:02,564 --> 01:20:04,699
I'm gonna show you racin'!
Come on.
Let it go!

1287
01:20:04,733 --> 01:20:06,168
And stay focused!

1288
01:20:12,541 --> 01:20:15,076
KEITH: A previous heat
had to be stopped
shortly after the start

1289
01:20:15,110 --> 01:20:17,546
because of an accident
that occurred
in the first turn.

1290
01:20:17,579 --> 01:20:20,148
The
Hallmark Homes
boat sank.

1291
01:20:20,182 --> 01:20:23,018
It's now at the bottom
of the Ohio River.

1292
01:20:23,051 --> 01:20:26,221
We'll be back for the running
of the next heat
in just a moment.

1293
01:20:26,254 --> 01:20:30,091
Second or third
in this heat
puts us in the final.

1294
01:20:30,125 --> 01:20:32,194
Well, then I'm really
gonna have to push her.

1295
01:20:32,227 --> 01:20:37,165
No, 3,700 RPMs,
that's all this old thing
has in her.

1296
01:20:37,199 --> 01:20:40,202
How do you expect me
to beat these guys
at three-quarters throttle?

1297
01:20:40,235 --> 01:20:43,171
You're the driver.
Figure it out.

1298
01:20:43,205 --> 01:20:46,908
KEITH: As the heat
gets underway,
Miss Madison
has a big problem

1299
01:20:46,942 --> 01:20:48,743
falling well off the pace.

1300
01:20:49,911 --> 01:20:51,913
Come on, Dad, pick it up.

1301
01:20:51,947 --> 01:20:54,382
KEITH:
Miss Madison
is lagging way behind

1302
01:20:54,416 --> 01:20:56,651
the other leaders,
almost a half lap.

1303
01:21:06,094 --> 01:21:07,429
Something's
gotta be wrong.

1304
01:21:13,435 --> 01:21:14,636
Right on it.

1305
01:21:19,608 --> 01:21:22,544
Up at the front,
Pay 'n Pak
coming hard,
taking the lead.

1306
01:21:22,577 --> 01:21:24,646
But look,
there's a puff of smoke.

1307
01:21:24,679 --> 01:21:26,748
That's a blown engine,
no question.

1308
01:21:26,781 --> 01:21:29,251
Pay 'n Pak's
gone,
coasting off the course.

1309
01:21:29,284 --> 01:21:31,553
With the
Pay 'n Pak
out,
third is all we need.

1310
01:21:31,586 --> 01:21:32,621
We're in the final heat.

1311
01:21:32,654 --> 01:21:34,589
We are in, guys.
We're in, Harry!

1312
01:21:34,623 --> 01:21:37,926
Just hope that
he can hold together
and finish, son.

1313
01:21:45,267 --> 01:21:48,169
KEITH: This could be
the miracle the Madison team
was hoping for

1314
01:21:48,203 --> 01:21:49,838
but
Madison's
got trouble.

1315
01:21:49,871 --> 01:21:51,740
They are down on power.

1316
01:21:51,773 --> 01:21:53,541
It's a struggle right now.

1317
01:21:55,176 --> 01:21:57,679
Just hold together
and finish.

1318
01:22:01,182 --> 01:22:02,450
Come on, baby!

1319
01:22:07,789 --> 01:22:11,493
Here comes
Madison,
smoke billowing out
of the engine now.

1320
01:22:11,526 --> 01:22:14,963
Will she make it?
Can she make it?

1321
01:22:18,500 --> 01:22:20,335
Come on, Jim! Come on!

1322
01:22:20,368 --> 01:22:22,170
(CROWD CHEERING)
The checkered flag.

1323
01:22:22,203 --> 01:22:26,441
McCormick's done it,
and
Madison
is in
the championship heat.

1324
01:22:26,474 --> 01:22:28,977
Congratulations on putting
the
Miss Madison
in the final heat

1325
01:22:29,010 --> 01:22:30,879
of a Gold Cup race
for the first time ever.

1326
01:22:30,912 --> 01:22:34,382
Well, thank you.
The guys have been
working awfully hard

1327
01:22:34,416 --> 01:22:36,951
and it's a tribute to them
that we're in it.

1328
01:22:36,985 --> 01:22:39,220
The
Budweiser
and the
Atlas
are the heavy favorites.

1329
01:22:39,254 --> 01:22:40,822
You've run
against them both today.

1330
01:22:40,855 --> 01:22:42,357
Who do you give the edge to?

1331
01:22:42,390 --> 01:22:45,160
Well, I'd like to think that
we'll have a say in that.

1332
01:22:45,193 --> 01:22:47,729
Is the Madison's strategy
to simply
stay out of the way

1333
01:22:47,762 --> 01:22:50,832
and hope to be running
at the finish?

1334
01:22:50,865 --> 01:22:54,202
Oh, hell, no.
We're out there to win,
just like everybody else.

1335
01:22:54,235 --> 01:22:56,171
KEITH: (LAUGHING)
That's the spirit, Jim.

1336
01:22:56,204 --> 01:22:59,074
All right, fellows,
let's go get set up
in the
Budweiser pit.

1337
01:22:59,107 --> 01:23:01,242
(ENGINE REVVING)

1338
01:23:10,485 --> 01:23:11,853
(SIGHING)

1339
01:23:23,498 --> 01:23:24,933
(EXHALING)

1340
01:23:26,835 --> 01:23:27,869
(SIGHING)

1341
01:23:28,837 --> 01:23:31,172
I gotta talk to you
about this final.

1342
01:23:31,906 --> 01:23:33,541
I don't wanna go home early.

1343
01:23:39,013 --> 01:23:40,281
I don't know,
Jimmy, it's...

1344
01:23:40,315 --> 01:23:41,983
You heard me, Harry.

1345
01:23:42,017 --> 01:23:43,151
We're not just
showin' up today.

1346
01:23:43,184 --> 01:23:45,186
You're driving
a stick of dynamite.

1347
01:23:45,220 --> 01:23:46,888
What else do you have?

1348
01:23:48,456 --> 01:23:49,791
(SIGHING)

1349
01:23:54,529 --> 01:23:56,531
Wanna go get
your drill-bit box?

1350
01:24:01,403 --> 01:24:02,937
(VALVE HISSING)

1351
01:24:02,971 --> 01:24:04,372
(WHIRRING)

1352
01:24:07,642 --> 01:24:10,478
TONY: Harry, isn't that one
awful big for the nitrous?

1353
01:24:13,248 --> 01:24:14,549
Wait, Jim, no.

1354
01:24:14,582 --> 01:24:16,851
This is my decision, guys.

1355
01:24:16,885 --> 01:24:18,453
We're gonna go,
or we're gonna blow.

1356
01:24:24,592 --> 01:24:26,261
Listen to me.

1357
01:24:26,294 --> 01:24:31,399
That white button,
only push that
if you're still racing.

1358
01:24:31,833 --> 01:24:33,001
You got me?

1359
01:24:33,635 --> 01:24:34,736
Okay.

1360
01:24:34,769 --> 01:24:37,138
Ought to call her
the
Miss Hindenburg.

1361
01:24:43,745 --> 01:24:45,413
What are you doin'?

1362
01:24:46,781 --> 01:24:48,283
What are you doin'?

1363
01:24:50,752 --> 01:24:53,588
How about I meet you
on this spot in 15 minutes?

1364
01:24:53,955 --> 01:24:55,390
Mmm-mmm.

1365
01:24:55,423 --> 01:24:59,327
Easy now. I don't want you
to be all smudged up
for the TV cameras.

1366
01:25:02,030 --> 01:25:06,267
We're gonna win.
We're gonna win.
For all of us.

1367
01:25:10,438 --> 01:25:11,773
HARRY: Hey, Jim.

1368
01:25:11,806 --> 01:25:13,308
I gotta go.

1369
01:25:13,341 --> 01:25:15,043
Let's do it.
I gotta go.

1370
01:25:25,787 --> 01:25:27,422
Harry.

1371
01:25:27,455 --> 01:25:29,224
Harry, what are you doin'?

1372
01:25:30,225 --> 01:25:31,893
He's gonna be fine.

1373
01:25:36,564 --> 01:25:37,866
Come on up.

1374
01:25:45,240 --> 01:25:46,307
We can do this!

1375
01:25:58,753 --> 01:26:01,856
(HYDROPLANES ROARING)

1376
01:26:10,732 --> 01:26:13,535
KEITH: Here they come.
It's a good start.

1377
01:26:13,568 --> 01:26:15,603
(CROWD CHEERING)

1378
01:26:34,923 --> 01:26:37,358
(ALL CHEERING)

1379
01:26:39,027 --> 01:26:41,829
Out of the fourth corner,
Miss Budweiser
extending her lead.

1380
01:26:41,863 --> 01:26:43,531
Coming down
the front stretch.

1381
01:26:43,565 --> 01:26:46,067
Appears to be
breaking away from the pack.

1382
01:26:46,100 --> 01:26:48,369
This could be
a runaway, folks.

1383
01:26:56,344 --> 01:26:58,546
(CROWD SCREAMING)

1384
01:27:00,615 --> 01:27:02,383
Madison p
assing
the
Notre Dame!

1385
01:27:02,417 --> 01:27:06,020
Now he's got
the second-place boat,
Cat's Pride,
in his sights.

1386
01:27:16,197 --> 01:27:21,202
Turn two, and the
Madison
now trails only the
Budweiser.

1387
01:27:21,903 --> 01:27:24,305
It's just you now, son.

1388
01:27:25,139 --> 01:27:27,108
You're all alone out there.

1389
01:27:35,116 --> 01:27:38,486
KEITH: Under the white flag.
One left to go.

1390
01:27:43,324 --> 01:27:46,294
Come on. You got it.
You got it, big guy.
Hold him back.

1391
01:27:50,598 --> 01:27:53,267
(REVVING)

1392
01:27:57,105 --> 01:28:00,141
(CROWD CHEERING)

1393
01:28:07,915 --> 01:28:10,918
KEITH: Rick Winston has gotta
feel Jim McCormick
on the back of his neck.

1394
01:28:10,952 --> 01:28:12,654
I mean, it's dead even.

1395
01:28:19,761 --> 01:28:21,929
You give him hell,
Jim McCormick!

1396
01:28:42,016 --> 01:28:44,952
KEITH: He's now coming down
the straightaway
towards the checkered flag

1397
01:28:44,986 --> 01:28:46,988
just a half a lap away.

1398
01:28:55,396 --> 01:28:56,864
Go, go, go!

1399
01:28:57,799 --> 01:28:58,833
Now!

1400
01:29:04,138 --> 01:29:07,375
Look at this. Look at this!

1401
01:29:11,479 --> 01:29:14,615
He may catch him.
He may catch him!

1402
01:29:14,649 --> 01:29:16,718
Come on!
Come on, Jim. Come on!

1403
01:29:19,721 --> 01:29:21,089
He got him!

1404
01:29:21,122 --> 01:29:23,658
(SCREAMING)
It's the
Madison
at the finish line!

1405
01:29:23,691 --> 01:29:27,195
(ALL CHEERING)
Madison
has won.

1406
01:29:27,228 --> 01:29:30,498
Miss Madison
has won
the Gold Cup.

1407
01:29:31,132 --> 01:29:34,769
(CROWD CHEERING)

1408
01:29:40,341 --> 01:29:42,744
Way to go, Dad! Yeah!

1409
01:29:56,124 --> 01:29:57,725
(WHOOPING)

1410
01:30:09,670 --> 01:30:10,938
He did it.

1411
01:30:12,273 --> 01:30:14,409
(ALL YELLING)

1412
01:30:14,442 --> 01:30:16,644
We did it! We did it!

1413
01:30:18,246 --> 01:30:19,614
Come on over here!

1414
01:30:29,423 --> 01:30:31,826
Jimmy, congratulations.
You never won one before

1415
01:30:31,859 --> 01:30:33,528
and you won the big one
in front of the home folks.

1416
01:30:33,561 --> 01:30:35,396
Thank you, Keith.
Well, we really wanted it.

1417
01:30:35,429 --> 01:30:38,766
Well, you guys were just
sitting there quietly,
watching everybody walk away

1418
01:30:38,800 --> 01:30:41,102
and then all of a sudden,
you're in the driver's seat.

1419
01:30:41,135 --> 01:30:43,771
Well, we were gonna go,
or we were
